    "translations": {
      "en": {
        "summary": "Imam al-Baqir (AS) praised his brother Zayd ibn Ali (AS) when the latter entered, declaring him a noble master of the Ahl al-Bayt and one who would seek retribution for the blood of the martyred Imams. This account, narrated through Abu al-Jarud who was personally present, serves as a historical validation of Zayd's uprising against the Umayyad oppressors, despite the theological differences between Zaydis and Twelver Shia. The praise 'truly noble is the mother who gave birth to you' is a traditional Arabic expression of high admiration for someone's character and lineage.",
        "key_terms": {
          "سَيِّدٌ": "Master, lord, or chief; also a title for descendants of the Prophet. Here it affirms Zayd's noble status within the Ahl al-Bayt.",
          "أَوْتَارِهِمْ": "Blood debts or vengeance; in classical Arabic, 'al-witar' refers to the duty of blood revenge. Here it signifies Zayd's role as the one who would seek justice for the martyrdom of the Imams.",
          "أَهْلِ بَيْتِهِ": "His household, referring to the Prophet's family (Ahl al-Bayt) — specifically here to the household of Imam Ali (AS)",
          "أَنْجَبَتْ": "A verb meaning 'to produce a noble child'; the expression 'truly noble is the mother who gave birth to you' is a classical Arabic form of high praise"
        },
        "seo_question": "What did Imam al-Baqir say about Zayd ibn Ali?"
